explanation: The humor hinges on re-phrasing the political cliché “the War on Christmas”—the claim that secular society is attacking that holiday—into “the War on Easter.” The bunny-suited employee is obviously meant to be the Easter Bunny, a living symbol of the holiday, but his appearance in a drab corporate corridor suggests he has just been fired, demoted, or otherwise forced to leave. description: In the cartoon, a person dressed in a full rabbit costume, carrying a briefcase and reading a sheet of paper, walks down a hallway in a typical office setting. Two business-suited colleagues stand nearby, looking somewhat puzzled, while another person peeks out from an office doorway.

explanation: The line mashes together two familiar office-life ideas: “Casual Friday,” when employees can ditch suits, and “Good Friday,” the Christian holiday that precedes Easter. Seeing the Easter Bunny—an over-the-top symbol of Easter—striding through a buttoned-up office already looks absurd. The speaker pretends this is simply someone taking advantage of a special dress-down day called “casual Good Friday,” as though the firm extends the Casual Friday policy to religious holidays and a full rabbit suit is an acceptable outfit. The joke comes from multiple incongruities: 1) no one actually has a “casual Good Friday”; 2) even on a casual day, a mascot costume is wildly inappropriate; and 3) the Easter Bunny belongs to Easter Sunday, not Good Friday, so the costume is thematically off. By acting as if this bizarre sight is merely an employee observing office policy, the caption humorously understates the ridiculousness and highlights how corporate jargon can be stretched to rationalize almost anything.

description: At a formal gathering, a stern-looking military officer with numerous medals and a cartoonishly long, receipt-like ribbon on his uniform holds a glass of wine. A woman in a black dress, also holding a glass of wine, is leaning in and speaking to him. Other guests are mingling in the background. The officer is speaking.
caption: I was stationed at CVS during the war on drugs.
element: The war on drugs typically refers to anti-narcotics government initiatives
explanation:
The caption turns two familiar ideas into a single pun.  
1. CVS is a pharmacy chain famous for giving customers absurdly long register receipts. The officer’s “ribbon bar” in the drawing has been exaggerated to look exactly like one of those receipts.  
2. “The war on drugs” is the U.S. government’s term for its military-style campaign against illegal narcotics.  

By saying he was “stationed at CVS during the war on drugs,” the officer pretends that working in a drugstore counted as military deployment in that war. The line melds literal combat language (“stationed,” “war”) with a completely mundane retail posting, and the absurdly long receipt on his chest visually backs up the story, as though each coupon line were a combat medal. The humor comes from re-imagining a pharmacist clerk as a decorated soldier and from the neat fit between CVS’s real-world receipts and the cartoon’s hyper-long service ribbon.
autograder_reasoning: The student’s answer explicitly mentions that "the war on drugs" refers to the U.S. government's campaign against illegal narcotics, aligning with the anticipated answer point. The student also connects this to the humor of the caption, thus capturing the key comedic element.
